In Detail: 

🟦 1. SUPERVISED LEARNING
You know the input (X) and output (Y).
 Used for prediction.
Two types:
A. Regression (Y is continuous)
B. Classification (Y is categorical)
Let’s break them down.

🔵 1A. REGRESSION ALGORITHMS (Predict continuous numerical values
✅ 1. Linear Regression
📌 Predicts a continuous number based on linear relationship.
How it works: Fits a straight line by minimizing squared error.
Use When: Trend appears linear, few features.
Avoid When:
Non-linear patterns
Many outliers
Multicollinearity
Examples: House prices, sales forecast.
✅ 2. Polynomial Regression
📌 Extension of linear regression that fits curves.
Use When: relationship between X and Y is non-linear.
✅ 3. Ridge Regression (L2 Regularization)
📌 Penalizes large coefficients → reduces overfitting.
Use When:
Multicollinearity
Need stable coefficients

✅ 4. Lasso Regression (L1 Regularization)
📌 Does feature selection by pushing coefficients to 0.
Use When:
Want to select important features
High dimensional data
✅ 5. Elastic Net Regression
📌 Combination of Ridge + Lasso.
Use:
When the dataset has both correlated & irrelevant features.
✅ 6. Decision Tree Regression
📌 Splits data into regions based on rules. Bases on if else statement
Use: Non-linear relationships, easy interpretation.
✅ 7. Random Forest Regression
📌 Ensemble of many trees → stable & accurate.
Use:
Complex relationships
Need high accuracy

✅ 8. Gradient Boosting Regression (XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost)
📌 Sequentially improves model by reducing previous errors.
Use:
Best performance for tabular data
Complex feature interactions

✅ 9. SVR (Support Vector Regression)
📌 Uses margin-based approach for regression.
Use:
High-dimensional data
Small/medium datasets

REGRESSION SUMMARY
Great for predicting:
Sales
Demand
Prices
Revenue
Temperature
Time duration



🔵 1B. CLASSIFICATION ALGORITHMS (Predict categories/labels)

✅ 1. Logistic Regression
📌 Predicts probability of a class (0/1).
Use:
Churn
Fraud
Spam

✅ 2. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
📌 Classifies based on nearest neighbors.
Use:
Small dataset
When classes are non-linear

✅ 3. Decision Tree Classifier
📌 Easy to interpret, handles non-linearity.
✅ 4. Random Forest Classifier
📌 Highly accurate, handles noise & overfitting.
✅ 5. Gradient Boosting Classifier (XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost)
📌 Best performance in classification tasks.
✅ 6. Support Vector Machine (SVM)
📌 Effective when classes are well-separated.
✅ 7. Naive Bayes
📌 What it is
Naive Bayes is a probabilistic classification algorithm based on Bayes’ Theorem, with the “naive” assumption that all features are independent of each other.
Despite this unrealistic assumption, it works extremely well for high-dimensional data, especially text.
Use:
Text classification
NLP sentiment analysis

CLASSIFICATION SUMMARY
Used for:
Fraud detection
Customer churn
Spam detection
Medical diagnosis
Credit approval




🟩 2. UNSUPERVISED LEARNING
No labeled outputs.
 Used for finding hidden patterns/structures.
Two main areas:
A. Clustering
B. Dimensionality Reduction

🟢 2A. CLUSTERING ALGORITHMS

✅ 1. K-Means Clustering
📌 Groups data into K clusters based on similarity.
How it works:
Chooses K centroids
Assigns points to closest centroid
Recalculates centroids
Use:
Customer segmentation
Pattern discovery
Avoid:
Non-spherical clusters
Outliers

✅ 2. Hierarchical Clustering
📌 Builds a tree (dendrogram) of clusters.
Use:
Small datasets
Want to visualize cluster hierarchy




✅ 3. DBSCAN (Density-Based Spatial Clustering)
📌 Finds clusters based on density; detects noise.
Use:
Geospatial data
Finding anomalies
Irregular shapes
Avoid:
High-dimensional data
Varying densities

✅ 4. Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM)
📌 Probabilistic clustering assuming data comes from Gaussian distributions.
Use:
Soft clustering (probabilities)
Overlapping clusters

CLUSTERING SUMMARY
Used for:
Customer segments
Fraud pattern discovery
Image grouping
Anomaly detection

🟢 2B. DIMENSIONALITY REDUCTION

✅ 1. PCA (Principal Component Analysis)
When you want to reduce dimensions while preserving maximum variance
When your features have multicollinearity
When you need faster model training on high-dimensional numerical data
When you need 2D/3D visualization of high-dimensional data



✅ 2. t-SNE
When you want to visually explore clusters in high-dimensional data
When relationships are non-linear
When working with embeddings, images, NLP vectors, or any complex feature space
When the goal is visualization only, not model training

✅ 3. UMAP
When you want t-SNE-level visualization but much faster
When you’re working with very large datasets
When preserving global + local structure is important
When generating embeddings for downstream ML tasks

🟧 3. SEMI-SUPERVISED LEARNING
Mixture of labeled + unlabeled data.
 Useful when labeling is expensive.

Algorithms include:
Pseudo-labeling
Semi-supervised SVM
Graph-based models
Use Cases:
Medical data (few labels)
Speech recognition
Web content classification




🟥 4. REINFORCEMENT LEARNING
Agents learn by interacting with the environment → rewards and penalties.
Key Algorithms:
Q-Learning
Deep Q Networks (DQN)
Policy Gradients
Actor-Critic Models
Use:
Robotics
Self-driving cars
Recommendation systems
Game AI

📘 Traditional NLP Algorithms
1. Bag of Words (BoW)
Converts text into a vector of word counts.
Ignore word order.
Simple baseline for text classification and spam detection.
2. TF-IDF
Weights words by importance:
Frequent in the document
Rare in the full corpus
Reduces impact of common stopwords ("the", "is").
Used for search ranking, text similarity, classification.
3. N-grams
Captures word sequences (bi-grams, tri-grams).
Adds context such as “not good”.
Improves over BoW by including word order.

📘 Embedding Models
1. Word2Vec
Learn dense vector embeddings based on context.
Words appearing in similar contexts have similar vectors.
Two architectures: CBOW and Skip-Gram.
2. GloVe
Embeddings trained using global co-occurrence statistics.
Better captures global structure than Word2Vec.
3. FastText
Consider subword information (character n-grams).
Handles rare words and misspellings better.
Great for languages with rich morphology.

📘 Deep Learning Models (Sequential)
1. RNN (Recrrent Neural Network)
Learn sequence data by maintaining hidden state.
Struggles with long-distance dependencies.
2. LSTM
RNN variant with memory cells + gates.
Solves vanishing gradient problem.
Good for text, time series, sequences.
3. GRU
Simplified LSTM (fewer gates).
Faster training, similar performance.
Used in NLP and sequence modeling.

📘 Transformer Models
1. BERT
Bidirectional transformer encoder.
Excellent for classification, NER, QA.
Learn context from both directions.
2. GPT
Decoder-only transformer.
Great for text generation, summarization, and dialogue.
3. RoBERTa
Optimized BERT with more training and data.
State-of-the-art for many NLP tasks.
4. T5
Text-to-text transformer:
Converts every task into text → text.
Very flexible across NLP tasks.

🟧 6. Time Series Models
📈 1. Classical Statistical Models
AR (AutoRegressive)
Forecasts using past values.
Example: today = a × yesterday + error.
MA (Moving Average)
Forecasts using past errors.
ARIMA
Combines AR + MA + differencing.
Good for non-stationary data.
SARIMA
ARIMA + seasonality.
Handles weekly/monthly/annual patterns.
ETS (Error, Trend, Seasonality)
Decomposes time series into 3 components.
Very interpretable.

📈 2. ML-Based Models
Random Forest for Time Series
Trains on lag features (t-1, t-2, etc.).
Handles non-linear patterns well.
XGBoost
Great for complex patterns.
Fast, accurate, widely used for competitions.

📈 3. Deep Learning Models
LSTM
Learn long-term patterns in time series.
Used for demand forecasting, stock prediction.
GRU
Faster LSTM alternative.
Transformers for Forecasting
Captures long-range dependencies better than LSTM.
Works well for multi-step and multivariate forecasting.

🟪 7. Anomaly Detection Algorithms
1. Isolation Forest
Isolates anomalies by randomly splitting data.
Anomalies get isolated in fewer splits.
Works great for high-dimensional data.
2. One-Class SVM
Learn a boundary around normal data.
Points outside boundary = anomalies.

3. Autoencoders
Neural network that reconstructs input.
Anomalies have high reconstruction error.
4. DBSCAN
Density-based clustering.
Points in low-density areas = anomalies.
Good for spatial/cluster data.
5. Z-score Based
Statistical method:
If a point is far from mean (in terms of standard deviations) → anomaly.
Works for simple numeric data.
Use Cases
Fraud detection
Network intrusion
Sensor anomaly / machine failure
Outlier detection in financial transactions
Healthcare anomaly detection



Model Selection
1️⃣ NUMERIC → Regression Models
Use when predicting continuous numbers.
✔ When data is linear
Linear Regression
 Use when relationships follow a straight line.
✔ When data is nonlinear
Polynomial Regression
Decision Tree Regressor


Random Forest Regressor
Gradient Boosting / XGBoost / LightGBM
✔ When data is large, and accuracy matters
XGBoost / CatBoost (best for Kaggle tabular data)
Neural Networks (if lots of features and nonlinearity)
✔ When features are correlated
Ridge / Lasso Regression
2️⃣ CATEGORICAL → Classification Models
✔ Binary classification (Yes/No)
Logistic Regression
SVM
Random Forest
XGBoost
Neural Networks
✔ Multi-class classification (3+ classes)
Random Forest
XGBoost
KNN
Naïve Bayes (text data)
Neural Networks


✔ High-dimensional text classification
Naïve Bayes
Logistic Regression
Transformer models (BERT)
⭐ STEP 2 — Is Your Data Sequential / Time-based?

3️⃣ Time-Series Models
If your data has a timestamp and ordering matters:
✔ Classical models
ARIMA / SARIMA
ETS
Holt-Winters
✔ Machine Learning based
XGBoost
Random Forest
✔ Deep Learning
LSTM
GRU
Temporal CNN
Transformers (Time-Series Transformers)


⭐ STEP 3 — No Target Variable → Unsupervised Learning
4️⃣ Unsupervised Models — No Labels
✔ Clustering
Use when grouping similar data:
K-Means
Hierarchical Clustering
DBSCAN (non-spherical clusters; noise in data)
✔ Dimensionality Reduction
Use to reduce features or visualize:
PCA
t-SNE
UMAP
✔ Anomaly Detection
Isolation Forest
One-Class SVM
Autoencoders

⭐ STEP 4 — Data Type Specific Models
